P: Well. Hmm. Ok. I’m just going to believe it. 

So, imagine for a moment that you are in 1773, like me. People like me are not so common a sight on these streets in London. I’m a young woman of 20, I’m a black woman, and I’m officially enslaved. My… well, I don’t know what to call them.  The… the people who bought me at the age of 7, the people who named me after the ship that brought me from West Africa to America, who still own every right to my humanity and movements… Those people are back in Boston. And for the first time, I’m away from their grasp. They’ve sent me over to London in the pursuit of getting my book published. I’m a poet, you see.  I’ve been writing poetry since I was a young girl and, well, not to blow my own horn but I’m very good at it. 

But there is another reason I’m in London, however. The book isn’t everything. 

Would you like to know the real reason I’m here?

