And we’re here. The Jamaica Coffee House. Maybe the name has changed in your era? I don’t know. 

I wish you could see what I’m seeing. The men. There are just so many of them inside of there, smoking their pipes, standing on tables, signing documents. This is their prime meeting spot, the great debating chamber of the empire. These men, in the heart of this great city of london, are debating the lives of millions - negotiating slave ship contracts, discussing insurrections, drinking their sugar-laden coffee. Millions of people just like me. Human beings, forced to be enslaved, to have their names and the lives taken away, stripped away from their home countries and their families, to work so hard to build everything you see around you today. It makes me sick.

I can’t let them see me. I just wanted to see these men for myself.  

I’m feeling such a mix of emotions right now, when I think about what is happening. 

I wonder - when you hear about this place, about the uglier sides and stories of London - what is your leading emotion, out of these three? 

